From adb3fbb4ff3f0d0ab3b4a15b2772ececf4dd015a Mon Sep 17 00:00:00 2001
From: David Allsopp <david.allsopp@metastack.com>
Date: Sat, 8 Feb 2025 16:48:35 +0000
Subject: [PATCH] Preserve backslashes in --prefix

Previously, the --prefix argument was always normalised with cygpath -m
which meant that regardless of the argument, the paths used in the
compiler would always use slashes.

This behaviour is preserved if a slash is detected in the argument, i.e.
the caller explicitly uses mixed notation (e.g. `--prefix=C:/Prefix` or
`--prefix $PWD/install`). In particular, it means that a Cygwin-style
path will be correctly converted to a Windows-style path.

If the path uses backslashes, then it is still converted to use forward
slashes for the installation commands, but the backslashes are otherwise
preserved and used within the build itself.

(cherry picked from commit 46b44c93d5891803b16f241b4b4bf0cab16414ab)

diff --git a/Changes b/Changes
index 216168d0db3cf41bb6284d5d2a631c99cb390c65..82dcca86f0a416426bee37bd578f55867a143405 100644
--- a/Changes
+++ b/Changes
@@ -72,10 +72,11 @@ OCaml 4.14 maintenance version
   --disable-shared.
   (David Allsopp, review by ???)
 
-- #14???: Normalise `--prefix` when compiling on MSYS2 in the same way as is
-  already done on Cygwin. In particular, backslashes are converted to slashes
-  and MSYS2-style paths (e.g. resulting from `--prefix $PWD/install`) are
-  converted to Windows-style paths.
+- #14???: When targeting native Windows on Cygwin or MSYS2, preserve
+  backslashes in the supplied `--prefix` (in particular, backslashes instead of
+  slashes will then be displayed by `ocamlopt -config-var standard_library`).
+  If the supplied prefix contains a slash, then it is normalised, as
+  previously.
   (David Allsopp, review by ???)
 
